results.notes:
Collected by Maricel Patino at the NJMA foray. Growing on dead wood (a fallen tree trunk). It had a very strong and pleasant, fragrant/perfumed odor (like bitter chocolate mixed with anise?), not dissimilar from some Agaricus species.
The collection was originally identified by Nina Burghardt as Psathyrella duchesnayensis, who referenced the C. du Q. website: https://www.mycoquebec.org/....
Doing some follow-up research, I found Smith’s original description of P. duchesnayensis in his Psathyrella study. [I updated the MO species record with it: https://mushroomobserver.org/name/show_name_description/14228]. This is where I came across Psathyrella cotonea. Regarding the two taxa Smith writes:
“[Duchesnayensis] is closest to Stropharia cotonea Quel. Kiihner and Romagnesi (1953) use this name to replace P. lacrymabunda and this is followed by Moser (1967). Quelets species was associated with conifers. Under the circumstances, however, there is nothing to be gained by trying to apply a confused concept of a European species to North American specimens. Kiihner and Romagnesi give the spores of their Drosophila cotonea as 7-8 (-10) x 3-4.5 (-5) m compared to 6-6.5 3-3.5 m for the Canadian species.
Surprisingly, Smith’s type of duchesnayensis has been sequenced (nrITS-LSU, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nuccore/KC992869). The full-length ITS sequence is 99.5-99.67% similar to two European accessions labeled as P. cotonea (AM712283 and KC992870)! So, are cotonea and duchesnayensis conspecific, or do they just happen to have essentially identical ITS sequences?
Back to the present collection… The spore print is brown. The spore dimensions are in line with those of P. cotonea, as the spores are clearly longer and wider than those reported by Smith for his species:
Mounted in Melzer’s and measured in profile (dorsi-ventral) view; [20/1/1]: L x W = 6.5~7.9 3.5~4 m; L’ x W’ = 7.25 × 3.74 m; Q = 1.75~2.13 (-2.20) m; Q’ = 1.94. Smooth, tawny-brown, inamyloid, non-gutulate, thin-walled (<0.25 m), without an apical pore, inequilateral (allantoid to bean-shaped) in profile view and oblong in face view, elongate to cylindric, with half of the spores having Q values of 2.00 and above. I saw just a handful spores under 7 m, and only two were in the proper orientation for measurement.
DNA Sequencing Results & Discussion (posted 16-May-21):
> A full-length consensus nrITS sequence of 601 base pairs (bps) was obtained from this collection by Dr. Kudzma from clean forward and reverse reads and posted this observation. “Consensus” means that each read spans the entire length of the locus and both are in 100% agreement with each other. ITS1 = 238 bps, 5.8S = 160 bps and ITS2 = 203 bps. The ITS region is preceded by the last 46 characters of nrSSU and followed by 86 characters of nrLSU. There is a single ambiguity, “Y” (C/T) at position #53 in ITS1.
> A BLASTn-100 search gave the following matching hits:
AM712283: ‘Psathyrella cotonea’ (from Czechia); 600/601 = 99.8% similarity
KC992870: ‘Psathyrella cotonea’ voucher LO136-00 (from Sweden?); 599/601 = 99.7% similarity
KC992869: ‘Psathyrella duchesnayensis’ voucher Smith61737 (from TYPE collection; Quebec, Canada); 598/601 = 99.5% similarity
Provided that the European collections have been correctly identified, P. duchesnayensis is likely synonymous with P. cotonea.

results.notes:
ID notes: keys to Caloplaca bolacina in Nash et al (2007). ID relies on my classification of exciple and thallus cortex as prosoplectenchymatous, both of which I’m fairly confident on, but not 100%. Thallus composed of convex, orange-yellow areoles also fits wells and points more toward bolacina than a Squamulea sp. I also considered C. marina for this, but that gets ruled out by the prosoplectenchymatous cortex (paraplect. in marina).

Spores polarilocular, hyaline, “septum” measurements: 4.3, 5.9, 2.9, 3 um (note: may need to be measuring the narrow “isthmus” instead of the gap between locules that I’m calling a septum here). Spore measurements: 13.9 × 4.8, 15.5 × 5.6, 15.7 × 6.0, 16.7 × 6.0 um

Thallus, orange-yellow, composed of scattered convex squamules/areoles. In section, thallus cortex is prosoplectenchymatous. Apothecia lecanorine, with thalline margin subtending proper margin. As far as I can tell, exciple below hypothecium and at margin is prosoplectenchymatous. (long, thin, tangled hyphae). Hymenium through hypothecium hyaline, subhymenium very faintly brownish but likely qualifies as hyaline. Epihymenium orange.
